Snipara uses a strict layered (clean/“onion”-style) architecture with a single allowed import direction and clearly separated responsibilities.

Core layers (top → bottom)
- Routes (apps/web/src/app/api/) — Thin HTTP handlers. Must:
  - Authenticate (requireAuth)
  - Validate input (Zod)
  - Delegate work to services or repository functions
  - Return a handled response
  - Example pattern:
    export async function POST(request: Request) {
      try {
        const user = await requireAuth();
        const body = schema.parse(await request.json());
        const result = await someService(body, user.id);
        return successResponse(result);
      } catch (error) {
        return handleError(error);
      }
    }

- Jobs / Orchestrators (lib/jobs/) — background processors / orchestration (can be imported by routes).

- Services (lib/services/) — External API adapters (e.g., Stripe). Use lazy initialization and retry logic; services talk to outside systems and are called from routes or jobs.

- Repositories (lib/db/queries/) — Centralized CRUD and permission-checked DB access. All DB access must go through this layer (never call Prisma directly from routes). Example: getProjectById(id, userId) enforces team membership.

- Types & Utils (types/, lib/utils/) — Shared pure utilities and type definitions. They must not depend on any other layer.

Key rules
- Import direction is one-way: higher layers can import lower layers, but lower layers cannot import higher layers.
- types/ and utils/ have no dependencies on other layers.
- All database queries live in lib/db/queries/ and include permission checks.
- Route handlers must be thin and delegate business logic to services/repositories.

Import hierarchy (from docs)
Routes (app/api/)
  ↓ imports
Services (lib/services/)
  ↓ imports
Repositories (lib/db/queries/)
  ↓ imports
Utils & Types — No dependencies

In short: a strict layered/clean-architecture pattern (Routes → Services → Repositories → Utils/Types) with enforced responsibilities and one-way imports.

Short answer: the API returns a 429 (Too Many Requests) error and includes rate/usage details so you can tell what was exceeded and when it resets.

Details:
- Monthly quota exceeded
  - Response: HTTP 429 with a body like:
    {
      "success": false,
      "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
      "usage": {
        "current": 101,
        "max": 100,
        "exceeded": true,
        "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
      }
    }
  - `usage.reset_at` is the ISO timestamp when the monthly quota resets.

- Per-minute (rate) limit exceeded
  - Response: HTTP 429 with error details such as:
    {
      "error": {
        "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
        "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
      }
    }
  - Some responses show: "Rate limit exceeded: 60 requests per minute".

- Other quota-style responses
  - When credits/queries are insufficient you may get an error object such as:
    {
      "error": { "code": "INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS", "message": "Need 5000 credits, have 5000" }
    }

- Rate-limit headers included on responses
  - X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset (seconds until reset or timestamp).

Recommended handling (brief)
- Check the rate headers, implement exponential backoff on 429s, cache/batch requests, or upgrade plan to avoid repeated 429s.

Short answer: the API returns a 429 (Too Many Requests) error and includes rate/usage details so you know how many queries were used and when limits reset.

Details (from the docs)

- Monthly query limit exceeded
  - Response: HTTP 429 with a JSON payload like:
    {
      "success": false,
      "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
      "usage": {
        "current": 101,
        "max": 100,
        "exceeded": true,
        "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
      }
    }
  - Fields:
    - current: current usage this billing period
    - max: allowed queries (-1 = unlimited)
    - exceeded: whether limit is reached
    - reset_at: ISO 8601 timestamp when monthly quota resets

- Alternative / credits-style response
  - When credits-style limits are enforced you may get:
    {
      "error": {
        "code": "INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS",
        "message": "Need 5000 credits, have 5000"
      }
    }

- Per-minute / rate-limit response
  - Exceeding per-minute limits returns a 429 with a short error object, e.g.:
    {
      "error": {
        "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
        "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
      }
    }
  - All responses include rate-limit headers you can monitor:
    - X-RateLimit-Limit — max requests/minute
    - X-RateLimit-Remaining — remaining in current window
    - X-RateLimit-Reset — seconds until the window resets (or a timestamp depending on endpoint)

Recommended immediate actions (from docs): check the rate headers, implement exponential backoff on 429s, cache or batch requests, or upgrade your plan if you need a higher quota.

Short answer
- The API returns HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) and refuses the request.

Details (monthly query limit)
- When a user exceeds their monthly query quota the API returns a 429 and a payload like:
  {
    "success": false,
    "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
    "usage": {
      "current": 101,
      "max": 100,
      "exceeded": true,
      "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
    }
  }
- Fields explained:
  - current: usage this billing period
  - max: allowed queries (−1 = unlimited)
  - exceeded: true when limit reached
  - reset_at: ISO timestamp when the monthly quota resets

Other related responses
- Some quota failures may use an INSufficient_CREDITS-style error:
  {
    "error": { "code": "INSUFFICIENT_CREDITS", "message": "Need 5000 credits, have 5000" }
  }
- For per-minute rate limits you may see a RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED error:
  {
    "error": { "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED", "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds" }
  }
  and responses include rate-limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset).

Recommended actions
- Check the rate-limit headers and the usage.reset_at value
- Implement exponential backoff on 429s
- Cache or batch requests and consider upgrading your plan if you need a higher quota.
